      {
         "id": "SECTION_non_quantum",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Classical Atomic Models\n\nThe deep study of atoms and the understanding of how the Universe is formed took millennia to develop. The first researcher we refer to is John Dalton (Livro 1). In his studies, Dalton concluded that matter is made up of small particles called atoms. In addition, by studying fluids, he inferred properties such as the weight of elements (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "97997331-20c2-4b5b-b13f-9677789dbb9d",
                     "text": "Dalton, John",
                     "page": "pp. 73",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1808",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"margin: auto; width: 100%;\"><iframe src=\"https://archive.org/details/newsystemofchemi01daltuoft/page/72/mode/2up\" width=\"100%\" height=\"560\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen=\"true\" mozallowfullscreen=\"true\" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Livro 1</b>: Page 73 of John Dalton’s work.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Another important advance in understanding atoms was made by J. J. Thomson, who, through experiments, discovered that atoms contain subatomic charged particles. This particle is known as the electron (<htcite0>).\n\nThomson also proposed a theory to explain why charged particles are deflected when passing through small amounts of matter — a theory later confirmed by Ernest Rutherford’s experiments. According to the proposed model, the atom consists of electrons orbiting a positively charged sphere concentrated at the center (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "638ebc79-9824-4485-a48b-f466f6aeaabf",
                     "text": "New, Charlotte",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2012",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "77a4d152-7328-47bb-bfea-1b1274649317",
                     "text": "Rutherford, Ernest",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1911",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 2: Building Rutherford’s Model</b><br /><br />We will use sheets of paper to recreate Graph 1.<br /><br />1. Take three sheets of the same size.<br /><br />2. Paint them in different colors.<br /><br />3. Choose one sheet and crumple it into a ball. It will represent the **nucleus of the atom.**<br /><br />4. Take another sheet, cut it into small equal pieces, and crumple them. Place them around the larger ball — these will represent the **electrons**.<br /><br />5. Repeat step 4 with the remaining sheet, and make the “electrons” follow paths <b>A</b>, <b>B</b> and <b>C</b> of the graph.</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"> <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"15\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"15\" font-size=\"1em\">A</text> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"134\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"134\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"134\" font-size=\"1em\">A</text> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"114\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"114\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"114\" font-size=\"1em\">A</text> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"64\" x2=\"115\" y2=\"64\" stroke=\"black\" />  <line x1=\"115\" y1=\"64\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"50\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"35\" y=\"50\" font-size=\"1em\">B</text>  <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"36\" x2=\"155\" y2=\"36\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"155\" y1=\"36\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"50\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"50\" font-size=\"1em\">C</text> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"30\"></circle> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"25\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"143\" y=\"27\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text>  <circle cx=\"75\" cy=\"75\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"73\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text> <text x=\"120\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> <text x=\"140\" y=\"60\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> <text x=\"140\" y=\"100\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text>  <text x=\"160\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> <circle cx=\"205\" cy=\"75\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"202\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text>  <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"125\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"143\" y=\"127\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text>  </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Representation of Rutherford model.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "Representação do átomo de Rutherford onde há um grande núcleo positivo e pequenos elétrons ao redor com carga negativa.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The Rutherford atomic model shows that the atom is not solid, but divided into two regions (<htcite0>): a dense, positively charged nucleus and an outer region where the negatively charged electrons are located.\n\nRutherford reached this conclusion by firing alpha particles (the “third crumpled balls” from Practice 2) at a gold foil. Observing the paths of these particles, he noticed that they could be deflected in different directions, indicating that atoms contain empty internal spaces (<htcite1>; <htcite2>), since if it were completely solid, the particles would not pass through it.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "77a4d152-7328-47bb-bfea-1b1274649317",
                     "text": "Rutherford, Ernest",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1911",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7cfbddbd-b600-4b9d-8ad5-dbaf7d508617",
                     "text": "The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica",
                     "page": "Rutherford Model",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "7",
                        "day": "18"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Science Is Practice</b><br /><br />The model developed by Democritus was a correct idea, but it was never tested in his time. For this reason, we cannot say he was truly doing science.<br /><br />When J. J. Thomson proposed a model and Ernest Rutherford tested it, improving our understanding, we saw science in action — theory being built through practice and experimentation.<br /><br />Have you ever heard the mistaken idea that science has no practical side?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
                {
               "text": "Although this atomic model with two regions explained some observations, it could not account for all the measurements made. In this context, in <htdate0>, James Chadwick conducted new experiments that demonstrated that, in addition to protons and electrons, there was another particle in the nucleus of the atom — a particle with no electric charge, which became known as the neutron (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b03b3ae2-51a7-4054-80ec-4e5c3ef83e58",
                     "text": "The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica",
                     "page": "James Chadwick",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "8",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1932",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
